#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
Nested participant-grouped Ricci classifier for active metabolic digraphs.

Feature representation
----------------------
For each sample s and each edge e in the maximal active edge universe:

    B_s(e)  = 1 if e is active/present in sample s, else 0
    K0_s(e) = kappa_s(e) if e is active/present in sample s, else 0

The classifier uses the sparse concatenated feature vector:

    X_s = [B_s | K0_s]

This is the Ricci representation described in the manuscript.

Validation protocol
-------------------
For each classification task:

    outer participant-grouped split:
        held-out test participants are never used for model selection

    inner participant-grouped validation split inside each outer train set:
        C and class_weight are selected by validation balanced accuracy
        macro F1 and ROC-AUC are tie-breakers

    refit:
        after hyperparameter selection, refit on all outer-training samples

    test:
        evaluate once on the outer-test samples

Interpretation tables
---------------------
After nested CV, the script chooses the most frequently selected hyperparameter
setting for each task, refits one model on all samples in that task, and writes
coefficient / process / top-edge tables for interpretation.

This final refit is for interpretation only. Test performance is always the
nested outer-fold performance.

Inputs
------
Ricci CSV files can use columns such as:

    a, b, k_ab

or

    source, target, kappa

One file per sample is supported. File names like CSM5XXXX_ricci.csv.gz are
used to infer sample_id when no sample_id column exists.

Optional process annotation
---------------------------
If the Ricci CSVs do not contain a process/category column, pass an optional
edge annotation CSV with columns such as:

    a,b,process

or

    edge,process

Otherwise process-level tables are still written but all edges are labelled
"Unannotated".
"""

